        <div align=3D"center">
        <br>
            <font color=3D"#3f0000"><b><font size=3D"+3">College Algebra</f=
ont></b> <br>
              <b><font size=3D"+3">Tutorial 37: </font></b></font><font col=
or=3D"#3f0000"><strong><font size=3D"+3">Synthetic Division and <br>
              the Remainder and Factor Theorems</font></strong><br>
              <br>
              </font>              <p></p>
        <p></p>
        <hr width=3D"100%">
        <div align=3D"left"><a href=3D"http://www.wtamu.edu/"><strong>WTAMU=
</strong></a> <strong>&gt; <a href=3D"http://www.wtamu.edu/mathlab">Virtual=
 Math Lab</a> &gt; <a href=3D"http://www.wtamu.edu/academic/anns/mps/math/m=
athlab/col_algebra/index.htm">College Algebra</a></strong>        </div>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
  <p align=3D"left">

    <b><font color=3D"#3366aa"><font color=3D"#3F0000" size=3D"+2"><img src=
=3D"https://www.wtamu.edu/academic/anns/mps/math/mathlab/col_algebra/desk%2=
0heading%20smaller.gif" alt=3D"desk" width=3D"50" height=3D"49">Learning Ob=
jectives</font></font></b>
</p><hr>
<p>
  </p><center>
  </center><table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cols=3D"=
1" width=3D"90%">
  <tbody><tr>
    <td> <div align=3D"left">After completing this tutorial, you should be =
able to:
      <ol>
        <li>To divide a polynomial by a binomial of the form&nbsp; <i><font=
 size=3D"+1">x</font></i> - <i><font size=3D"+1">c</font></i> using synthet=
ic division.</li>
        <li> Use the Remainder Theorem in conjunction with synthetic divisi=
on to find
          a functional value.</li>
        <li> Use the Factor Theorem in conjunction with synthetic division =
to find factors
          and zeros of a polynomial function.</li>
        </ol>
    </div>      </td>
  </tr>
</tbody></table>

<br><br>
<br><br>
<p align=3D"left"><b><font color=3D"#3366aa"><font color=3D"#3F0000" size=
=3D"+2"><img src=3D"https://www.wtamu.edu/academic/anns/mps/math/mathlab/co=
l_algebra/desk%20heading%20smaller.gif" alt=3D"desk" width=3D"50" height=3D=
"49">Introduction</font></font></b>
</p><hr>
<center>
  <br>
</center>
<center>
  <table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cols=3D"1" width=
=3D"90%">
    <tbody><tr>
      <td><div align=3D"left">In this tutorial we are going to look at synt=
hetic division.&nbsp;
You can use synthetic division whenever you need to divide a polynomial
function by a binomial of the form <i><font size=3D"+1">x</font></i> - <i><=
font size=3D"+1">c</font></i>.&nbsp;&nbsp;
We can use this to find several things.&nbsp; One is the actual quotient
and remainder you get when you divide the polynomial function by <i><font s=
ize=3D"+1">x</font></i> - <i><font size=3D"+1">c</font></i>. Also, the Rema=
inder Theorem states that
the remainder that we end up with when synthetic division is applied actual=
ly
gives us the functional value.&nbsp; Another use is finding factors and
zeros.&nbsp; The Factor Theorem states that if the functional value is
0 at some value <i><font size=3D"+1">c</font></i>, then <i><font size=3D"+1=
">x</font></i> - <i><font size=3D"+1">c</font></i> is a factor and <i><font=
 size=3D"+1">c</font></i> is a zero.&nbsp; You can not only find that funct=
ional value by using synthetic
division, but also the quotient found can help with the factoring process.&=
nbsp;
Sounds like synthetic division can help us out on several different types
of problems.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I think you are ready to go discover the
wonderful world of synthetic division.</div></td>
    </tr>
  </tbody></table>
</center>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p align=3D"left">
<b><font color=3D"#3366aa"><font color=3D"#3F0000" size=3D"+2"><img src=3D"=
https://www.wtamu.edu/academic/anns/mps/math/mathlab/col_algebra/desk%20hea=
ding%20smaller.gif" alt=3D"desk" width=3D"50" height=3D"49"> Tutorial</font=
></font></b>
</p><hr>
<p><a name=3D"synthetic"></a> <br>
  &nbsp;
</p><center>
  <table border=3D"" cols=3D"1" width=3D"40%" bgcolor=3D"#FFFFCC">
    <tbody><tr>
      <td><center>
        &nbsp;<b><font size=3D"+1">Synthetic Division</font></b>
      </center></td>
    </tr>
  </tbody></table>
</center>
<br>
&nbsp;
<center>
  <table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cols=3D"1" width=
=3D"90%">
    <tbody><tr>
      <td><div align=3D"left">Synthetic division is another way to divide a=
 polynomial by the binomial <i><font size=3D"+1">x</font></i> - <i><font si=
ze=3D"+1">c</font></i> , where <i><font size=3D"+1">c</font></i> is
        a constant.</div></td>
    </tr>
  </tbody></table>
</center>
<p><a name=3D"step1"></a> <br>
  &nbsp;
</p><center>
  <table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cols=3D"1" width=
=3D"90%">
    <tbody><tr>
      <td><div align=3D"left"><b><font size=3D"+1"><font color=3D"#CC0000">=
Step 1:</font> Set up the synthetic
        division.</font></b></div></td>
    </tr>
  </tbody></table>
</center>
<br>
&nbsp;
<center>
  <table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cols=3D"1" width=
=3D"80%">
    <tbody><tr>
      <td><div align=3D"left">An easy way to do this is to first set it up =
as if you are doing long
        division and then set up your synthetic division.
      </div>
        <p align=3D"left">If you need a review on setting up a long divisio=
n problem, feel free
          to go to <b><a href=3D"https://www.wtamu.edu/academic/anns/mps/ma=
th/mathlab/col_algebra/col_alg_tut36_longdiv.htm#step1" target=3D"_blank">T=
utorial 36: Long
            Division.</a></b>
          </p><p align=3D"left">The divisor (what you are dividing by) goes=
 on the outside of the box.&nbsp;
            The dividend (what you are dividing into) goes on the inside of=
 the box.&nbsp;
          </p><p align=3D"left">When you write out the dividend make sure t=
hat you write it in descending
            powers and you insert 0's for any missing terms.&nbsp; For exam=
ple, if
            you had the problem&nbsp;<img src=3D"https://www.wtamu.edu/acad=
emic/anns/mps/math/mathlab/col_algebra/col_alg_tut37div1.gif" alt=3D"synthe=
tic division" width=3D"144" height=3D"26">,
            the polynomial&nbsp;<img src=3D"https://www.wtamu.edu/academic/=
anns/mps/math/mathlab/col_algebra/col_alg_tut37div2.gif" alt=3D"synthetic d=
ivision" width=3D"74" height=3D"20">,
            starts out with degree 4, then the next highest degree is 1. It=
 is missing
            degrees 3 and 2.&nbsp; So if we were to put it inside a divisio=
n box we
            would write it like this:
          </p><center>
            <p align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.wtamu.edu/academic/=
anns/mps/math/mathlab/col_algebra/col_alg_tut37div3.gif" alt=3D"synthetic d=
ivision" width=3D"193" height=3D"30">.&nbsp;
            </p></center>
        <p>This will allow you to line up like terms when you go through th=
e problem.&nbsp;
          </p><p>When you set this up using synthetic division write <i><fo=
nt size=3D"+1">c</font></i> for the divisor <i><font size=3D"+1">x</font></=
i> - <i><font size=3D"+1">c</font></i>.&nbsp;
            Then write the coefficients of the dividend to the right, acros=
s the top.&nbsp;
            Include any 0's that were inserted in for missing terms.
          </p><center>
            <p><img src=3D"https://www.wtamu.edu/academic/anns/mps/math/mat=
hlab/col_algebra/col_alg_tut37div4.gif" alt=3D"synthetic division" width=3D=
"415" height=3D"75">
            </p></center></td>
    </tr>
  </tbody></table>
</center>
<p><a name=3D"step2"></a> <br>
  &nbsp;
</p><center>
  <table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cols=3D"1" width=
=3D"90%">
    <tbody><tr>
      <td><div align=3D"left"><b><font size=3D"+1"><font color=3D"#CC0000">=
Step 2:</font>&nbsp; Bring down
        the leading coefficient to the bottom row.</font></b></div></td>
    </tr>
  </tbody></table>
</center>
<br>
&nbsp;
<center>
  <table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cols=3D"1" width=
=3D"80%">
    <tbody><tr>
      <td><center>
        <img src=3D"https://www.wtamu.edu/academic/anns/mps/math/mathlab/co=
